es quickly adjust to reflect all known information.\n\nIn another scenario, think about the producers of a low-cost item. Suppose Joan makes jewelry boxes and sells them cheaply. If someone buys her jewelry boxes and sells them at a higher price elsewhere, that's also arbitrage. This practice might reduce Joan's potential to make higher-end sales because buyers might go for the seller who re-sells her boxes at an inflated price.\n\nTo sum it up: information asymmetry \u2192 opportunities for arbitrage \u2192 potential for bad deals for uninformed parties. In efficient markets, where information is freely and equally available, arbitrage opportunities are minimal because everyone knows about all the price differences promptly.",
