          "content": "To understand the concept of classes and functions as introduced in this textbook excerpt, we'll start by building a foundational understanding that will lead us to comprehend how classes and functions work together in Python programming.\n\n### Prerequisite Concepts\n\n1. **Basic Data Types**:\n   - In programming, data can come in various types such as numbers, strings, lists, etc. Each type serves different purposes and can be used to perform specific tasks.\n\n2. **Objects and Attributes**:\n   - An object is an instance of a class. Just like you can have multiple light bulbs of the same type, you can have multiple objects of the same class.\n   - Objects have attributes, which are like properties that describe that object. For example, a `Car` object could have attributes like `color`, `model`, and `year`.\n\n3. **Functions**:\n   - Functions are blocks of code designed to perform a particular task. They take inputs, called parameters, and can return an output. For example, a function to add two numbers might take two numbers as input and return their sum.\n\n### Main Concept: Classes and Objects in Python\n\nPython allows programmers to define their own data types using classes. A class acts as a blueprint for creating objects (specific instances of the class). Let's explore how this works with the example of a `Time` class.\n\n#### Defining a Class\n\nThe class `Time` is designed to represent the time of day. The class definition in Python looks like this:\n\n```python\nclass Time:\n    \"\"\"Represents the time of day.\n    Attributes: hour, minute, second\n    \"\"\"\n```\n\n- **Attributes (hour, minute, second):** Think of attributes as variables that are bound to objects from this class. These will store information about the object's state.\n\n#### Creating and Using Objects\n\nYou can create an object of the `Time` class and assign values to its attributes as follows:\n\n```python\ntime = Time()\ntime.hour = 11\ntime.minute = 59\ntime.second = 30\n```\n\nThis object `time` now represents the time 11:59:30.\n\n#### Concrete Example with Functions\n\nLet's look at an example to put this into context. Suppose you want to add the duration of a movie to a start time to find out when the movie will end.\n\n```python\ndef add_time(t1, t2):\n    sum = Time()\n    sum.hour = t1.hour + t2.hour\n    sum.minute = t1.minute + t2.minute\n    sum.second = t1.second + t2.second\n    \n    # Handle the case where the seconds or minutes are 60 or more\n    if sum.second >= 60:\n        sum.second -= 60\n        sum.minute += 1\n    if sum.minute >= 60:\n        sum.minute -= 60\n        sum.hour += 1\n        \n    return sum\n```\n\n- **Pure Function:** `add_time` is an example of a pure function because it doesn't modify the input objects; instead, it creates and returns a new `Time` object.\n\n- **Example Use Case:**\n  ```python\n  start = Time()\n  start.hour = 9\n  start.minute = 45\n  start.second = 0\n\n  duration = Time()\n  duration.hour = 1\n  duration.minute = 35\n  duration.second = 0\n\n  done = add_time(start, duration)\n  # This should return an object representing 11:20:00\n  ```\n\n#### Modifiers\n\nModifiers are functions that modify the objects they receive as parameters. For example, if you want to add a certain number of seconds to a `Time` object, you may write:\n\n```python\ndef increment(time, seconds):\n    time.second += seconds\n    while time.second >= 60:\n        time.second -= 60\n        time.minute += 1\n    while time.minute >= 60:\n        time.minute -= 60\n        time.hour += 1\n```\n\n- **Modifier Function:** `increment` modifies the input `Time` object directly, so it doesn't need to return anything.\n\n### Linking Concepts\n\n- **Classes & Objects**: Provide a way to model real-world entities and their interactions.\n- **Functions**: Allow performing operations on objects, enhancing reusability and simplifying complex logical operations.\n\nBy using classes and functions together, you can create organized, modular, and efficient programs that mimic real-world scenarios. This helps tackle complex problems by breaking them down into manageable pieces.",
