ns for `k` and `(n-k)`.\n- You can view this formula as ways to arrange elements (with order considered) divided by the redundancies caused by rearranging the selected elements, thus only counting unique combinations.\n\n### Example and Linking Ideas\n\n**5. Linking The Ideas with an Example:**\n- Suppose you have `n = 5` students and you want to choose `k = 2` students to form a team. Applying the formula:\n\n  \\[\n  C(5,2) = \\frac{5!}{2!(5-2)!} = \\frac{5 \\times 4 \\times 3 \\times 2 \\times 1}{2 \\times 1 \\times 3 \\times 2 \\times 1} = \\frac{120}{12} = 10\n  \\]\n\n- So, there are 10 possible ways to choose 2 students out of 5.\n\n**6. The Concept of Ordered Lists:**\n- If the order was important, each selection could be ordered in `k!` (factorial of `k`) different ways, as described in the concept of making ordered k-lists. This involves permutations where the sequence matters.\n  \n  For instance, if selecting and ordering the team, the student list `{A, B}` becomes `{A, B}` and `{B, A}` as two different arrangements (or permutations).\n\nBy understanding how to calculate combinations using binomial coefficients and how factorials help us manage the permutations in ordering, you can solve a variety of problems involving counting and arranging elements from a set.",
