^2 + 2ab + b^2\n   \\]\n\nThis is the expanded form of \\((a + b)^2\\), demonstrating how the binomial theorem distributes terms according to the combinations of \\( a \\) and \\( b \\).\n\n### Connecting Ideas:\n\nThe factorial concept is tied to combinations because combinations are calculated using factorials. These combinations or binomial coefficients help distribute terms in a polynomial expansion as per the binomial theorem. Solving or expanding expressions using this theorem becomes crucial in algebra, calculus, and various applications in probability and statistics.\n\nBy verifying the theorem for specific values of \\( n \\) like \\( 1, 2, \\) and \\( 3 \\), you develop a better understanding, further supported by techniques like mathematical induction to validate it for all natural numbers \\( n \\). This example helps build a solid foundation for further studies in algebra and analysis.",
