ses rotation, and thus you apply torque.\n- If you push at the center of the wheel (at the axle), there\u2019s no rotation, hence no torque is applied.\n\nTorque depends on two main factors:\n1. The magnitude of the force applied.\n2. The distance from the axis of rotation (the pivot point) where the force is applied.\n\nThe unit of torque is the newton-meter (Nm), which happens to be the same as the unit of energy, but they describe different physical concepts.\n\n### Connecting to Angular Momentum\n\nWith this understanding in place, we're ready to approach angular momentum, which extends the idea of linear momentum into the realm of rotational motion. Angular momentum, much like linear momentum, is a measure of the quantity of rotation an object has. It depends on the object's rotation speed, mass distribution, and shape, and it's analogous to linear momentum but applied to rotating systems.\n\nThese foundational concepts of momentum, force, and torque, will help you understand how objects behave when they spin and how they interact with forces that might change that spin\u2014leading us into the study of angular momentum in future discussions.",
