 of rotation), which increases the torque.\n\n### Connecting to Angular Momentum\n\nNow that we understand momentum, force, and torque, we can connect these ideas to angular momentum. Just as momentum is a measure of motion in a straight line, angular momentum is a measure of rotation. It depends on:\n- **The mass of the object**,\n- **The velocity at which it's rotating**,\n- **How far the mass is from the axis of rotation**.\n\nFor a spinning figure skater, when they pull their arms in, they reduce the distance of their mass from the axis of rotation, thereby increasing their rotation speed while conserving angular momentum.\n\nIn summary, angular momentum is to rotating objects what linear momentum is to objects moving in a straight line. Understanding momentum, force, and torque is crucial for grasping how objects move and rotate both in everyday experiences and in complex systems like planetary motion.",
